The root cause is iOS Safari's **"text field zoom" behavior** triggered when:

1. An input's font size is **below 16px** (or computed to be below 16px)
2. The viewport's `user-scalable` isn't explicitly disabled
3. The input receives focus on a touch device

In your case, the computed `~13px` font size triggers iOS to automatically zoom into the input for "readability" on touch devices.

## Solutions

### 1. **Recommended: Increase font size to ≥16px** (no accessibility tradeoff)
```css
.desk-input {
  font-size: 16px; /* Minimum size to prevent auto-zoom */
  /* Or use 1rem if your root font-size is 16px */
}
```
This is the cleanest solution with **no accessibility downsides** — larger text is actually better for readability on mobile.

### 2. **Disable zoom with maximum-scale (not recommended)**
```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, maximum-scale=1.0">
```
**Accessibility tradeoff:** This prevents users from zooming the page entirely, which violates WCAG 2.1 Success Criterion 1.4.4 (Resize Text) and 1.4.10 (Reflow).

### 3. **Use 16px on focus only (hacky workaround)**
```css
.desk-input {
  font-size: 13px; /* Normal size */
}

.desk-input:focus {
  font-size: 16px; /* Prevents zoom */
}
```
**Tradeoff:** Visual jump when focusing, which can be disorienting.

### 4. **Use `inputmode` with smaller font (modern approach)**
```html
<input type="text" class="desk-input" inputmode="text">
```
Some reports suggest `inputmode="text"` or `inputmode="none"` can prevent zoom even with smaller fonts, but this isn't consistently reliable across iOS versions.

## Additional Considerations for Capacitor/WKWebView

Since you're using Capacitor, also check:

1. **Capacitor Configuration** (`capacitor.config.ts`):
```typescript
ios: {
  contentInset: 'never'
}
```

2. **Add CSS to prevent text size adjustment**:
```css
html {
  -webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%; /* Prevent font scaling in landscape */
}

.desk-input {
  -webkit-appearance: none; /* Remove iOS styling */
  touch-action: manipulation; /* Improve touch responsiveness */
}
```

## Recommended Implementation

```css
/* In your styles.css */
.desk-input {
  font-size: 16px; /* Primary fix */
  font-family: inherit; /* Keep your inherited font */
  line-height: 1.4; /* Maintain comfortable spacing */
  -webkit-appearance: none;
  border-radius: 0; /* Optional: Remove iOS rounded corners */
}

/* Optional: Scale down visually while keeping 16px */
.desk-input.small-visual {
  transform: scale(0.8125); /* 13px/16px = 0.8125 */
  transform-origin: left top;
  width: 123%; /* Counteract scaling (1/0.8125 ≈ 1.23) */
}
```

The **16px font solution is best** — it solves the zoom issue while maintaining or improving accessibility. Test with VoiceOver to ensure the input remains fully usable.

The root cause is **iOS Safari's (and WKWebView's) text input auto-zoom behavior**. When a user taps an input field with a font size **less than 16px**, iOS automatically zooms the viewport to make the text readable, but in a Capacitor/WKWebView app, this can cause the page to get "stuck" zoomed in because:

1. The `.desk-input` inherits a body font size of ~13px (below the 16px threshold)
2. iOS zooms in on focus to make the text readable
3. In a WKWebView app, the typical pinch-to-zoom back out may be disabled or behave unexpectedly
4. The viewport gets locked in a zoomed state

## The Fix:

Add to your CSS:
```css
.desk-input {
  font-size: 16px; /* Force minimum 16px font size */
  /* OR use 16px on mobile only with a media query */
}

/* Alternative: Use a media query for mobile */
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  .desk-input {
    font-size: 16px;
  }
}
```

## Alternative Solutions (if changing font size isn't desirable):

1. **Disable zoom entirely** (not recommended for accessibility):
```css
.desk-input {
  font-size: 16px; /* Still needed */
  /* Prevent iOS zoom */
  touch-action: manipulation;
}

/* In JavaScript or meta tag */
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, maximum-scale=1.0, user-scalable=no">
```
**Warning:** This harms accessibility by preventing users from zooming.

2. **Use `inputmode`** (modern approach):
```html
<input class="desk-input" inputmode="text">
```
This can help iOS choose appropriate keyboard without triggering zoom.

3. **Prevent zoom with JavaScript** (hacky):
```javascript
document.querySelector('.desk-input').addEventListener('focus', function() {
  document.querySelector('meta[name="viewport"]').setAttribute('content', 
    'width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, maximum-scale=1.0');
});
```

## Accessibility Tradeoff:

**Changing font size to 16px+**:
- ✅ Maintains pinch-to-zoom functionality
- ✅ Improves readability for low-vision users
- ✅ Follows WCAG guidelines (1.4.4 Resize Text)
- ⚠️ May break your design if not accounted for

**Disabling zoom entirely**:
- ❌ Harms accessibility (violates WCAG 1.4.4)
- ❌ Users with low vision cannot zoom in further
- ✅ Preserves exact design proportions

## Recommended Solution:

Use a mobile-specific media query to set `font-size: 16px` only on mobile devices, and consider using `inputmode` for better keyboard handling. This maintains accessibility while preventing the unwanted zoom behavior.

```css
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  .desk-input {
    font-size: 16px;
    /* Optional: improve touch targets */
    min-height: 44px; /* Apple's recommended minimum touch target */
  }
}
```

This addresses the iOS-specific issue while keeping your desktop design intact and maintaining full accessibility.

Looking at the issue, here's what's happening:

## The Problem
1. **Image aspect ratio**: 9:16 = 0.5625 (tall and narrow)
2. **Container aspect ratio**: 3:4 = 0.75 (less tall than the image)
3. **`object-fit: cover` behavior**: When the container and image have different aspect ratios, `cover` scales the image to completely fill the container, cropping any excess.

Since your container (3:4 = 0.75) is **wider** than your image (9:16 = 0.5625), `object-fit: cover` scales the image up until it fills the container horizontally. This causes the image to become taller than the container vertically, so the top and bottom get cropped.

## The Fix

You have a few options:

### Option 1: Change container aspect ratio (Recommended)
If you want to show the full photo strip without cropping:
```css
.cover-card {
  aspect-ratio: 9 / 16; /* Match the image ratio */
}
```

### Option 2: Use `object-fit: contain` instead
This will show the entire image but may leave empty space:
```css
.cover-card img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: contain; /* Shows whole image, adds letterboxing */
  background-color: #f0f0f0; /* Optional: Add background for empty space */
}
```

### Option 3: Adjust cropping with `object-position`
If you must keep 3:4 but want to control what gets cropped:
```css
.cover-card img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: cover;
  object-position: center 30%; /* Adjust vertical focus point */
}
```

### Option 4: Use a wrapper with overflow (Flexible)
If you need dynamic sizing:
```css
.cover-card {
  aspect-ratio: 3 / 4;
  overflow: hidden;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center; /* Centers vertically */
  justify-content: center; /* Centers horizontally */
}

.cover-card img {
  width: 100%;
  height: auto; /* Maintains image aspect ratio */
  /* OR height: 100%; width: auto; depending on which dimension to prioritize */
}
```

**Recommendation**: Use **Option 1** if you can control the container aspect ratio, as it will preserve the entire photo strip without any cropping. If you need to maintain the 3:4 container for design consistency, **Option 4** with `height: 100%; width: auto;` might work best, though it will leave horizontal empty space on the sides.

Short answer:
The cover is cropped because the image’s aspect ratio (9:16) doesn’t match the card’s aspect ratio (3:4). With object-fit: cover, the browser fills the 3:4 area and crops whatever doesn’t fit, which removes the top and bottom of a tall 9:16 strip.

Fix options:
- If you want the entire strip visible without cropping: use object-fit: contain (optionally add a background to fill the empty space).
- If you want to keep the 3:4 card but avoid top/bottom loss: change the image’s aspect ratio to 3:4 when generating it.
- If you must keep both ratios and cropping is acceptable: adjust focal point with object-position so the most important part isn’t clipped.

Drop-in fix (keep 3:4 card, show full strip):
.cover-card {
  aspect-ratio: 3 / 4;
  background: #000; /* or your brand bg */
}
.cover-card img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: contain; /* shows the whole strip; may letterbox */
  object-position: center top; /* optional: bias toward top */
}

If you can change the card ratio to match the strip:
.cover-card {
  aspect-ratio: 9 / 16; /* match the strip */
}
.cover-card img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: cover; /* now no cropping of top/bottom */
}

Notes:
- object-fit: cover always crops to fill the box; the only way to avoid it is to either match the aspect ratios or switch to object-fit: contain.
- If you keep 3/4 and switch to contain, you’ll get horizontal or vertical letterboxing depending on the image; style the card’s background to make it look intentional.

Reason:
- object-fit: cover scales the image to fill the element while preserving its aspect ratio, then crops whatever overflows.
- Your image is 9:16 (taller), but the .cover-card is 3:4 (shorter/wider). To “cover” the wider container, the browser centers-crops the top and bottom of the tall image, showing only a middle band.

Fix:
Make the container match the image’s aspect ratio so cover doesn’t need to crop.

Option A: Match the image aspect ratio (recommended)
- Change .cover-card to aspect-ratio: 9 / 16.

Option B: Show the whole image (no crop)
- Use object-fit: contain (you’ll get letterboxing/pillarboxing).

Option C: Keep the container but control the crop
- Use object-position: top or bottom to choose which part is kept.

Executable examples:

Option A (no crop)
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8" />
<style>
.cover-card {
  width: 240px;
  aspect-ratio: 9 / 16; /* match the image */
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  overflow: hidden;
}
.cover-card img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: cover; /* now no cropping because ratios match */
  display: block;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="cover-card">
    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1529626455594-4ff0802cfb7e?auto=format&fit=crop&w=720&h=1280&q=80" alt="9:16 strip">
  </div>
</body>
</html>

Option B (contain, no crop but with padding)
